# **01  How Foofoo personas work**

Foofoo has two layers of user understanding that operate simultaneously and serve different purposes:

| **Layer** | **Audience** | **What it contains** | **Used for** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Qualitative personas (this document)** | Product, Design, Marketing, Engineering | 5 named archetypes with full day-in-the-life context, before/after states, and journey maps | Feature prioritisation, UX decisions, marketing messaging, test case design |
| **Backend cohort system (V2 RE engine)** | Engineering, Data | 41 backend personas mapped to 36 states, household types, and diet patterns | Recommendation engine segmentation, plan generation, cold-start defaults |

The user never sees backend personas. They answer 5 natural onboarding questions. The engine silently maps their answers to one of 41 personas and begins generating plans. The qualitative personas in this document represent the most common archetypes within that mapping.

| **The five personas, by priority:** Meera — The family meal planner (P0 — MVP is built for her) Riya — The busy solo professional (P1a — highest daily engagement potential) Arun — The fitness-focused solo (P1b — highest premium conversion potential) Vikram — The college student (P2a — highest referral velocity) Priya — The health-conscious new mother (P2b — highest willingness to pay for Premium Plus) |
| --- |

# **02  Persona 1 — Meera, the family meal planner**

| **Priority: P0  ·  Every MVP feature is tested against: ****'****Would Meera use this daily?****'**** If the answer is no, it does not ship.** |
| --- |

| **Meera** *The family meal planner — 32, Pune* |
| --- |
| **Age ****&**** city** | 32 years old, Pune. Originally from Bhopal, Madhya Pradesh. |
| **Household** | Husband (IT professional, works long hours), daughter aged 5, son aged 8. In-laws visit for 2–3 months/year. |
| **Occupation** | Primary homemaker and part-time work-from-home (data entry). Manages all household meals. |
| **Income** | Household income ₹1.2–1.8L/month. Food budget ₹18,000–22,000/month. |
| **Devices** | Android smartphone (mid-range). WhatsApp is her primary communication channel. |
| **V2 cohort** | MC_FAMILY → SC_COUPLE_WITH_SCHOOL_CHILD. Home state: Madhya Pradesh. Current city: Pune. |
| **Diet** | Vegetarian. No major allergies. In-laws are strict vegetarian during Navratri. |
| **Cook capability** | Confident cook — cooks 2–3 meals daily, 7 days a week, from scratch. |

## **Day in the life — before Foofoo**

| **Time** | **What Meera does** | **What she feels** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **6:30 AM** | Wakes up. Immediately starts thinking: 'Aaj kya banaye?' No plan. Opens YouTube, searches 'easy breakfast recipe'. 15 minutes gone. | Anxious, slightly resentful. This happens every single day. |
| **7:00 AM** | Settles for poha — again — because it's safe and quick. Kids complain it's the same thing. | Guilty. Boring. Like she's failed already. |
| **9:30 AM** | School run done. Thinks about lunch. Husband messages asking what's for lunch. She hasn't decided. | Pressured. Annoyed at the question she has no answer for. |
| **10:00 AM** | Scrolls Instagram recipe reels. Finds something interesting but realises she doesn't have half the ingredients. | Defeated. Opens Swiggy to check if ordering is cheaper. |
| **12:30 PM** | Makes dal-chawal — the backup meal when she can't decide. Kids eat it. Nobody complains but nobody's excited. | Resigned. It's fine. Just fine. |
| **4:00 PM** | Starts worrying about dinner. Texts mother in Bhopal for a suggestion. Gets a recipe she doesn't have the time for. | Exhausted. It's a daily cycle with no system. |
| **7:00 PM** | Makes sabzi-roti. Reasonable meal. Husband says 'it's good.' Kids want something different. | Tired but relieved it's over. Dreads tomorrow morning. |

## **Day in the life — with Foofoo (Day 30)**

| **Time** | **What Meera does** | **What she feels** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **6:30 AM** | Phone notification: 'Your family's meals for today are ready.' Opens Foofoo. Sees Methi Thepla (breakfast — it knows she makes quick flatbreads on weekdays), Dal Palak + Roti (lunch), Aloo Matar Sabzi + Rice (dinner). | Calm. Relieved. The decision is already made. |
| **6:35 AM** | Doesn't like the dinner suggestion — used aloo yesterday. Swipes to see alternatives. Picks Paneer Bhurji + Roti. Locks it. | Satisfied. It took 5 minutes including thinking. |
| **6:40 AM** | Checks grocery list. Needs fresh paneer. Messages husband to pick up on his way home. | In control. Day is planned before it starts. |
| **12:00 PM** | Cooks lunch exactly as planned. No deliberation, no searching. | Efficient. Lunch in 25 minutes, no decision overhead. |
| **7:00 PM** | Dinner is Paneer Bhurji + Roti — planned since morning. Cooks without thinking about it. | Proud. Kids love paneer. Husband asks why dinner feels more 'intentional' lately. |
| **8:00 PM** | Swipes tomorrow's breakfast in 2 minutes before bed. Done. | Empowered. First time she has a plan before the day starts. |

