## **Before / after — Meera**

| **Before Foofoo** Spends 15–20 minutes deciding every morning Repeats same 8–10 dishes in rotation Feels guilty about boring meals Makes last-minute Swiggy orders out of indecision No system — pure reactive daily stress | **After Foofoo** Plan is ready before she wakes up Genuine variety driven by regional intelligence Cooks confidently with a plan Swiggy order is a choice, not an escape First time she has a system for meals |
| --- | --- |

## **What Meera needs for Premium conversion**

Meera's free-to-premium trigger is not price — it is value density. She upgrades when she sees that Premium unlocks family analytics ('which dishes do my kids accept vs reject'), weekly meal insights ('your family ate 4 paneer dishes this week — here are alternatives'), and family profile management (managing in-laws' Navratri constraints separately). Target: Phase 1.5 activation.

# **03  Persona 2 — Riya, the busy solo professional**

| **Priority: P1a  ·  Highest daily engagement potential. Her use pattern (daily, quick, decisive) validates the core loop faster than any other persona.** |
| --- |

| **Riya** *The busy solo professional — 28, Mumbai* |
| --- |
| **Age ****&**** city** | 28 years old, Mumbai (Bandra). Originally from Jaipur, Rajasthan. |
| **Household** | Lives alone. Nuclear. No dependents. |
| **Occupation** | Product Manager at a Series B startup. 10+ hour workdays, frequent WFH. |
| **Income** | ₹18–24L/year. Food budget ₹12,000–16,000/month — of which ₹7,000–9,000 is Swiggy/Zomato. |
| **Devices** | iPhone (latest model) + Android work phone. Heavy app user. UPI autopay for 6+ subscriptions. |
| **V2 cohort** | MC_SOLO → SC_WORKING_PROFESSIONAL. Home state: Rajasthan. Current city: Mumbai. |
| **Diet** | Vegetarian. No allergies. Occasionally eats eggs. Tries to eat healthy but doesn't track calories. |
| **Cook capability** | Intermediate — can cook but rarely does. 'Cook' means assembling rather than making from scratch. |

## **Day in the life — before Foofoo**

| **Time** | **What Riya does** | **What she feels** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **8:00 AM** | Wakes up. Immediately checks Slack. No breakfast plan. Skips it or grabs whatever's in the fridge. | Busy, distracted. Food is not a priority at 8 AM. |
| **1:00 PM** | Lunch meeting ends. Starving. Opens Swiggy. Scrolls for 18 minutes. Biryani? Too heavy. Salad? Too expensive. Orders the same thali she orders every Tuesday. | Decision fatigue. Annoyed at herself for being predictable. |
| **8:30 PM** | Work done. Opens Zomato. Scrolls. Nothing looks right. Orders a burger because it's easy. | Guilt. She wanted to cook something. Just didn't know what. |
| **9:00 PM** | Eats while watching Netflix. Thinks: 'I should cook more. But I never know what to make.' | Resolved to do better. Won't. Same tomorrow. |

## **Day in the life — with Foofoo (Day 14)**

| **Time** | **What Riya does** | **What she feels** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **7:50 AM** | Notification: 'Your breakfast for today — Besan Chila. 3 ingredients. 10 minutes.' Opens app. Locks it. Adds eggs to the ingredient list. | Impressed. Decided in 20 seconds. Rajasthan-influenced breakfast without being a cliché. |
| **12:50 PM** | Check app for lunch suggestion before opening Swiggy. Sees: Dal Makhani + Jeera Rice. Doesn't have time to cook. Taps 'Order instead'. Foofoo deeplinks to Swiggy with the dish pre-searched. | Efficient. Still used Swiggy, but the decision was made in 10 seconds, not 18 minutes. |
| **8:15 PM** | Opens app for dinner. Sees Paneer Tikka Wrap — quick, uses leftover paneer in the fridge. Cooks it in 15 minutes. | Proud. Actually cooked. App used her pantry context. |

## **What makes Riya unique as a persona**

Riya's interaction pattern is different from Meera's. She is not planning a family — she is solving a daily solo decision. Her key behaviours: quick morning check (under 60 seconds), frequent 'order instead' taps rather than cooking, and high swipe activity as she browses alternatives. Her engagement proves the core loop works for the non-cooking use case — Foofoo as the decision layer before Swiggy, not as a cooking guide.

| **Before Foofoo** 18-minute Swiggy scroll to decide what to order Guilt about ordering the same thing again Eats well when she has time, badly when busy No connection between what she eats and how she feels | **After Foofoo** Meal decision in under 60 seconds Orders intentionally — chose that dish, not the default Occasionally cooks because the decision is already made Starts noticing patterns in what she actually likes |
