# **04  Persona 3 — Arun, the fitness-focused solo**

| **Priority: P1b  ·  Highest premium conversion potential. Fitness users have the clearest articulated need and the strongest willingness to pay for a product that demonstrably helps them hit goals.** |
| --- |

| **Arun** *The fitness-focused solo — 24, Bengaluru* |
| --- |
| **Age ****&**** city** | 24 years old, Bengaluru (Koramangala). Originally from Coimbatore, Tamil Nadu. |
| **Household** | Lives alone, PG accommodation with basic kitchen (hob, no oven). |
| **Occupation** | Software developer, 2 years experience. Gym 5 days/week, 6:00–7:30 AM. |
| **Income** | ₹12–16L/year. Food budget ₹8,000–10,000/month. Spends ₹2,000/month on protein supplements. |
| **Devices** | Android mid-range. Uses MyFitnessPal but frustrated by poor Indian food data. |
| **V2 cohort** | MC_SOLO → SC_FITNESS_FOCUSED + O_HIGH_PROTEIN_OVERLAY. Home state: Tamil Nadu. Current city: Bengaluru. |
| **Diet** | Non-vegetarian but prefers South Indian base foods. Needs 150g+ protein/day for muscle building. |
| **Cook capability** | Intermediate — can cook simple meals but limited by PG kitchen and time after gym. |

## **Core pain point**

Arun knows he needs high protein. He knows Indian food can provide it — eggs, paneer, dal, chicken, fish. What he cannot figure out is which combination of Indian meals gives him 150g protein daily without eating boiled chicken breast twice a day. Every nutrition app he tries gives him Western meal suggestions. MyFitnessPal's Indian food database is incomplete for home-cooked food. He ends up eating the same 5 meals on rotation because they're the ones he's calculated manually.

## **What Arun needs from Foofoo**

- Protein-first meal suggestions that still feel like real Indian food — not generic 'grilled chicken + salad'

- Calorie and macro display on every dish card — non-negotiable

- South Indian food bias in suggestions (he eats dosa, idli, sambar, rasam — not just dal-chawal)

- Quick cook suggestions — post-gym breakfast in under 15 minutes with his basic kitchen setup

- Equipment-aware recommendations — no suggestions requiring a pressure cooker or oven

## **Arun****'****s phase unlock path**

| **Phase** | **Feature Arun gets** | **Why it converts him** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **MVP** | South Indian dish bias from Tamil Nadu home state. Basic dish cards with simple macros. | First time an app suggests idli-sambar as a valid high-protein breakfast. |
| **Phase 1** | Calorie targeting toggle. Fitness mode (boosts protein-dense dish scoring). Macro breakdown in Meal Detail. | Can now see his protein intake across the day from Indian food. Replaces MyFitnessPal. |
| **Phase 1.5** | Premium tier — full nutrition analytics. Weekly protein trend. Smart meal sequencing for training days vs rest days. | Pays ₹99/month because the analytics are worth it. No equivalent in the market. |

| **Before Foofoo** Eats same 5 meals on rotation — safe but boring Manually calculates macros in a spreadsheet MyFitnessPal doesn't know what 'pesarattu' is Buys expensive supplements because he can't hit protein from food alone | **After Foofoo** South Indian high-protein suggestions he actually wants to eat Macros visible on every card — no spreadsheet App understands his food culture and his fitness goal Learns which Indian dishes hit his targets — reduces supplement spend |
| --- | --- |

# **05  Persona 4 — Vikram, the college student**

| **Priority: P2a  ·  Highest referral velocity. College students are India****'****s most powerful word-of-mouth network. One engaged user on a campus creates 20–50 downloads.** |
| --- |

| **Vikram** *The college student — 20, Delhi* |
| --- |
| **Age ****&**** city** | 20 years old, Delhi (hostel, Karol Bagh area). Originally from Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh. |
| **Household** | Hostel room. Basic kitchen: electric hot plate, electric kettle. No pressure cooker, no mixer. |
| **Occupation** | 3rd year engineering student. 6 roommates, all from different states. |
| **Income** | ₹8,000–10,000/month pocket money from parents. Food budget ₹3,000–4,000/month. |
| **Devices** | Android budget phone. Heavy WhatsApp and Instagram user. Uses UPI for all payments. |
| **V2 cohort** | MC_SOLO → SC_STUDENT_HOSTEL + O_SIMPLE_EQUIPMENT_OVERLAY. Home state: Uttar Pradesh. Current city: Delhi. |
| **Diet** | Non-vegetarian but eats whatever is available. Budget is the primary constraint. |
| **Cook capability** | Beginner — can make basic things on a hot plate. Limited by equipment and skill. |

## **The equipment overlay — why this matters for Vikram**

The O_SIMPLE_EQUIPMENT_OVERLAY is a hard filter applied to all of Vikram's suggestions. If a dish requires a pressure cooker (rajma, chole), an oven (baked dishes), a mixer (chutneys, smoothies), or more than one pan simultaneously, it is filtered out before scoring. This is not a preference — it is a capability constraint. Suggesting Rajasthani Dal Baati to a student with a hot plate and a kettle destroys trust in one interaction. The overlay prevents this.

Vikram's suggestions: Instant Maggi upgrades (adding egg, vegetables), poha (kettle-soaked), bread-egg preparations, packaged dal with rice (hot plate), curd rice (no cooking needed). These feel humble but they are exactly right for his context. An app that respects his constraints earns his loyalty and his referrals.

## **Vikram****'****s referral value**

Vikram's hostel has 400 students. If 3% of them download Foofoo from his referral link in month 1, that is 12 users with zero marketing spend. College WhatsApp groups, Instagram story shares of funny or relatable meal plans, and the social proof of 'my roommate showed me this app' are Vikram's contribution to Foofoo's growth model.

| **Before Foofoo** Eats hostel mess food 2x/day — bored and sometimes disgusted Can't cook recipes he finds online — wrong equipment Overspends on canteen when he can't figure out what to make Skips breakfast because deciding is harder than skipping | **After Foofoo** Suggestions that actually work on his hot plate Budget-first sorting — sees ₹30–50 meals first Breakfast in 10 minutes with 3 hostel-available ingredients Shares meal plan with roommates — group cooking moments |
| --- | --- |

# **06  Persona 5 — Priya, the health-conscious new mother**

| **Priority: P2b  ·  Highest willingness to pay for Premium Plus. The postpartum/pregnancy use case is underserved and high-stakes — users in this context have both the need and the means to pay.** |
| --- |

| **Priya** *The health-conscious new mother — 30, Chennai* |
| --- |
| **Age ****&**** city** | 30 years old, Chennai. Originally from Chennai — home state and current city are the same. |
| **Household** | Husband (works in finance), infant daughter (3 months old). Lives with mother-in-law. |
| **Occupation** | On maternity leave from IT job. Returns to work in 3 months. |
| **Income** | Household income ₹2L+/month. Food budget ₹20,000–25,000/month. |
| **Devices** | iPhone. Active health app user — uses HealthifyMe for calorie tracking. |
| **V2 cohort** | MC_FAMILY → SC_COUPLE_WITH_INFANT + O_POSTPARTUM_OVERLAY. Home state: Tamil Nadu. Current city: Chennai. |
| **Diet** | Non-vegetarian. South Indian food identity. Has lactation-support dietary requirements. |
| **Cook capability** | Confident cook. Mother-in-law also cooks. Joint cooking household. |

## **The postpartum overlay — Foofoo****'****s most nuanced feature**

The O_POSTPARTUM_OVERLAY is a member add-on, not a replacement for the family meal plan. This is the critical architectural distinction from V2. Every existing app that attempts to serve postpartum nutrition converts the entire user's diet into a postpartum plan — methi ladoo for breakfast, moringa soup for lunch, ajwain water for dinner. This is medically informed but practically useless for a family household.

Foofoo's approach: the primary family meal (South Indian, Tamil-rooted, normal food) remains unchanged. The postpartum overlay generates add-on components for Priya's slots:

- Breakfast add-on: warm methi ladoo or sesame til laddoo (lactation support, traditional South Indian postpartum)

- Lunch add-on: extra calcium-rich side (ragi porridge, drumstick sambar prioritised)

- Dinner add-on: turmeric milk or ajwain water

The family eats normal food. Priya gets her postpartum support alongside it. Nobody's meal plan is replaced by a medical diet. This is a household product, not a clinical one.

## **Why Priya converts to Premium Plus**

Priya is already paying ₹999/month for HealthifyMe. She understands the value of a health-aware food app. Foofoo's Premium Plus at ₹149/month is a fraction of that price, and it solves a different problem: the family meal decision, not individual calorie tracking. The postpartum feature alone — if it works correctly — is worth ₹149/month to a new mother who previously had to manually research what to add to her daily meals.

| **Before Foofoo** Every app gives her a 'postpartum diet plan' that replaces her normal food — she doesn't want that Has to manually add postpartum foods to her daily normal meals Mother-in-law suggests traditional foods but they're not always practical to cook HealthifyMe tracks calories but doesn't understand she's also feeding a family | **After Foofoo** Family eats normal South Indian meals. Priya gets postpartum add-ons alongside — not instead One plan covers the whole household including her recovery needs Traditional postpartum foods surfaced in culturally appropriate forms (Tamil region defaults) Uses Foofoo for family meal planning; HealthifyMe for individual calorie tracking — complementary |
| --- | --- |

# **07  Persona priority matrix ****&**** feature mapping**

| **Persona** | **MVP feature** | **Phase 1** | **Phase 1.5** | **Phase 2** | **Revenue priority** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Meera — Family planner** | Household plan, member add-ons, regional identity | Family profile UI, weekly variety insights | Family analytics, Premium Plus features | Multi-gen profiles, pantry system | Medium CAC, high LTV — word-of-mouth in housing societies |
| **Riya — Solo professional** | Quick plan, 'order instead' CTA, swipe speed | Mood selector, faster morning UX | Premium tier (ads-free, insights) | Voice assistant, 'cooking for guests' mode | Low CAC (social), medium LTV — high churn risk if not habitual |
| **Arun — Fitness solo** | South Indian dish bias, basic macros | Fitness mode, calorie targeting, macro breakdown | Full nutrition analytics, training-day planning | Health profiles, dietician access | Medium CAC, high LTV — pays for performance |
| **Vikram — Student** | Equipment overlay, budget-first suggestions, hostel-friendly meals | Student mode (quick, cheap, minimal equipment) | Premium via referral stacking (free months) | Batch cooking suggestions for hostel | Low CAC (referral), low LTV — converts when earning |
| **Priya — New mother** | Postpartum overlay, family plan with add-ons | Health profiles (pregnancy, postpartum) | Premium Plus (household + health profiles) | Dietician access, recovery meal plans | Low CAC (recommendation from doctor/community), very high LTV |

# **08  How to use these personas — the product test questions**

Every feature decision, every design choice, and every sprint prioritisation should be run through the following questions. If a feature cannot answer at least one of them, it should not be in the MVP.

| **Test question** | **What it screens for** | **Who applies it** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Would Meera use this daily?** | Core loop quality — does it solve the recurring daily problem or is it a one-time feature? | Product, Engineering |
| **Would Riya use this in under 60 seconds?** | Speed and friction — is the interaction fast enough for a high-frequency, low-time user? | Design, Engineering |
| **Does this make Arun****'****s macro tracking easier?** | Depth and intelligence — does the feature add measurable value for a data-oriented user? | Product, Data |
| **Would Vikram****'****s hostel roommates hear about this?** | Virality and shareability — is this a feature people talk about? | Marketing, Product |
| **Does this respect Priya****'****s household complexity without medicalising her meals?** | Household intelligence — does the feature serve the whole household, not just one member? | Product, Engineering |

